Goal:
The following vpu tests are created to maximize vpu functional coverage and target a wide range of functionality. They exercise
VPU specific operations and tensor operations. The test with ust in their name are targeted for the UST flow and are designed to finish
in ~1-2 days in simulation and 2 hours on the Zebu platform and have coverage of ~60%+.
The non-UST tests should be run in the most general setting possible (for example, full-chip environment).
The combined expected coverage of these tests is above 80% for vpu related cover-groups and above 70% for overall ET-SOC functional coverage.
The _<X>h_ specifies how many HART(s) are active in the tests. More details are available in the README file.

Detail(s):
vpu tests are divided into directories by the number of threads they target:
dv/tests/minion_core/c_asm_tests/vpu/1h
dv/tests/minion_core/c_asm_tests/vpu/2h
dv/tests/minion_core/c_asm_tests/vpu/16h
dv/tests/minion_core/c_asm_tests/vpu/64h

The number of threads increase successively from 1 thread to 1 minion core to 1 neighborhood to 1 shire.
Currently, hartid's are hardcoded into the test to target the following: 
1h tests: hart0 of  minion0 of neigh0 of shire0 
2h tests: all threads of minion0 of neigh0 of shire0, 
16h tests: all threads of all cores of neigh0 of shire0, 
64h tests: all threads of all cores of all neighs of shire0, 

These tests only access legal DRAM memory locations as per memory map and initialize all memory locations accessed by the test.
This is to avoid memory related exceptions (if any memory exceptions happen in the test execution, they are unintentional and a possible test bug) 
and to bring data into faster levels of memory. When data hits in L1/L2/L3 caches for the most part, the tests can stress the vpu datapaths and
functionality aggressively rather than idling on memory access service requests.
The tests have a simplistic exception handler that simply returns control flow back to the instructions after an excepting instruction.

Dependencies are created by manipulating the source and destination register addresses of the adjacent instructions.  For e.g.,

			"fmul.s f26, f15, f25, rne\n"
			"fexp.ps f12, f21\n"
			"fmul.s f15, f9, f15, rup\n"

The tests have a limited amount of self-checking. Each test has a seq counter and counts the number of sequences executed. 
At the end of the test, the total number of sequences are checked against the expected sequences executed. 
Some of the tensor fma sequences involving integer data have expected results and check the registers against the expected values. 
None of the tensor sequences are expected to generate tensor errors, and will jump to TEST_FAIL if any tensor_errors happen in the test.

